# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: government-agency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Adjudication can also refer to the processes at dance competitions, in television game shows and at other competitive forums, by which competitors are evaluated and ranked and a winner is found.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Adjudication may be defined as "the legal process of resolving a dispute.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The formal giving or pronouncing of a judgment or decree in a court proceeding; also the judgment or decision given.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The entry of a decree by a court in respect to the parties in a case.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] It implies a hearing by a court, after notice, of legal evidence on the factual issue(s) involved; it may be equivalent to a determination.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] It indicates that the claims of all the parties there to have been considered and set at rest." In some cases, an application for adjudication is an alternative legal process instead of applying for a court hearing.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Each state and territory has enacted security of payment legislation which provide for adjudication of progress construction claims, starting with New South Wales in 1999.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] There is very little harmony between the legislation in each jurisdiction regarding the scope of contract covered and the adjudication procedure.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] However, in all jurisdictions, adjudications are interim pending final resolution of the dispute under the relevant terms of the contract.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The *Building and Construction Industry Security of Payment Act 1999* came into effect in New South Wales on 26 March 2000 and applies to all construction contracts commenced on or after that date.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] It is not possible to contract out of the legislation.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Amendments to the Act made in 2013 are not retrospective, however, earlier amendments are.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The Act does not apply to mining work, however, construction work ancillary to the operation of a mine is covered.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The Act also does not apply to work undertaken for a resident owner within the meaning of the *Home Building Act 1989*.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] In NSW, the 2016 case of *Probuild Constructions (Aust) Pty Ltd v Shade Systems Pty Ltd* has allowed an adjudicator's determination for a non-jurisdictional error to be overturned through judicial review.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The case went against *Brodyn Pty Ltd v Davenport* (2004), which had held that judicial intervention was limited to cases of a breach of essential and basic requirements.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The Building and Construction Industry Payments Act 2004 (BCIPA) came into effect in Queensland in October, 2004.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Through a statutory-based adjudication process a claimant can seek to resolve payment on account disputes.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The act covers construction, and related supply of goods and services, contracts, whether written or verbal.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] BCIPA is regulated by the Building and Construction Industry Payments Agency, a branch of the Queensland Building Services.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Adjudication is a relatively new process introduced by the government of Victoria, Australia, to allow for the rapid determination of progress claims under building contracts or sub-contracts and contracts for the supply of goods or services in the building industry.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] This process was designed to ensure cash flow to businesses in the building industry, without parties getting tied up in lengthy and expensive litigation or arbitration.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] It is regulated by the Building and Construction Industry Security of Payment Act 2002.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Builders, sub-contractors and suppliers need to carefully choose a nominating authority to which they make an adjudication application.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Adjudication is used in relation to construction disputes in Nigeria, although there is no statutory framework for adjudication under Nigerian law.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Lawyers at Stren & Blan Partners note that "recent trends indicate a shift towards adjudication, exemplified by notable settlements in major construction disputes".
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The relevant legislation in regard to construction in the United Kingdom is the Housing Grants, Construction and Regeneration Act 1996 (1996 Chapter 53), later amended by Part 8 of the Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Any party to a construction contract has the right to refer a dispute arising under the contract to a third party for adjudication, whose decision shall be binding unless the courts or an arbitrator have already made a determination on the referred issue.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The Act does not define "adjudication" or an "adjudicator", but an adjudicator's obligation is to act "impartially" (section 108(2)(e)).
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The parties can agree between themselves who will undertake the adjudication, but where they cannot agree, either party may ask an **Adjudicator Nominating Body** (ANB) to appoint one.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] In Scotland, the Scheme for Construction Contracts (Scotland) Regulations 1998 apply.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] For there to be a dispute capable of being addressed by adjudication, "it must be clear that a point has emerged from the process of discussion or negotiation that has ended and that there is something which needs to be decided".
[src:government-agency/adjudication] In the case of *Aspect Contracts (Asbestos) Limited (Respondent) v Higgins Construction Plc (Appellant)*, heard in 2015, the Supreme Court of England and Wales argued that the wording would have been clearer if had said "unless and until" instead of merely "until".
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The phrase "true value adjudication" is sometimes used in relation to the role of an adjudicator, meaning that the adjudicator is asked to determine the true value of a completed construction where this may be different from the value claimed by the contractor and/or paid by the client.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] In other circumstances, an adjudicator's ruling is binding and a point which has been resolved cannot be raised again, but where the adjudicator went outside the scope of the adjudication referred to them, their comments were not a binding part of the ruling.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] In the same case, reference is made to a 2006 Court of Appeal ruling, *Carillion Construction v Devonport Royal Dockyard*, in which Lord Justice Chadwick reminded litigants that in the UK context, "the majority of adjudicators are not chosen for their expertise as lawyers.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Their skills are as likely (if not more likely) to lie in other disciplines.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The task of the adjudicator is not to act as arbitrator or judge.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The time constraints within which he is expected to operate are proof of that.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] "Claims adjudication" is a phrase used in the insurance industry to refer to the process of paying claims submitted or denying them after comparing claims to the benefit or coverage requirements.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The adjudication process consists of receiving a claim from an insured person and then utilizing software to process claims and make a decision or doing so manually.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] If it is done automatically using software or a web-based subscription, the claim process is called auto-adjudication.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Automating claims often improve efficiency and reduce expenses required for manual claims adjudication.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Many claims are submitted on paper and are processed manually by insurance workers.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] After the claims adjudication process is complete, the insurance company often sends a letter to the person filing the claim describing the outcome.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The letter, which is sometimes referred to as remittance advice, includes a statement as to whether the claim was denied or approved.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] If the company denied the claim, it has to provide an explanation for the reason why under regional laws.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The company also often sends an explanation of benefits that includes detailed information about how each service included in the claim was settled.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Insurance companies will then send out payments to the providers if the claims are approved or to the provider's billing service.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] The process of claims adjudication, in this context, is also called "medical billing advocacy".
[src:government-agency/adjudication] It may be determined that the person is not suitable for a public trust position, but is suitable for a non-sensitive position.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] However, a person may be deemed unsuitable for any position.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Referring to a minor, the term **adjudicated** can refer to children who are under a court's jurisdiction, usually as a result of having engaged in delinquent behavior and not having a legal guardian that could be entrusted with being responsible for him or her.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] A child dependency or neglect adjudication can also result in a determination that a child is in need of services.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Different US states have different processes for declaring a child as adjudicated.
[src:government-agency/adjudication] Arizona state law defines a dually adjudicated child as "a child who is found to be dependent or temporarily subject to court jurisdiction pending an adjudication of a dependency petition and who is alleged or found to have committed a delinquent or incorrigible act".
[src:government-agency/adjudication] According to Illinois state law, "adjudicated" means that the Juvenile Court has entered an order declaring that a child "is neglected, abused, dependent, a minor requiring authoritative intervention, a delinquent minor or an addicted minor".
[src:government-agency/administration-government] The term **administration**, as used in the context of government, differs according to the jurisdiction under which it operates.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] In general terms, the administration can be described as a decision-making body.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] The term "administration" has been used to denote the executive branch in presidential systems of government.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] The term's usage in Europe varies by country.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] Still, most typically the word "administration" refers to managerial functions in general, which may include local governments, or the hierarchy of national and local government, that applies to a town or district.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] More specifically, it may refer to public administration, the business of administering public policy as determined by the government.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] However, outside France and Romania, this usage of the word is uncommon.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] For the British sense of the word, most countries use the term *government*, referring to the "administration" of Winston Churchill as the "Churchill government".
[src:government-agency/administration-government] This is also true for the non-European members of the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] An older, chiefly Commonwealth usage, is the term "ministry", as in "Churchill Ministry", which is still in official and academic use in Britain, Australia, and Canada to refer the terms of prime ministers.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] The word coalition may be used for a specific government depending on the type of government.
[src:government-agency/administration-government] In the Netherlands, cabinet is the most-used term (as in "the fourth Balkenende cabinet").
[src:government-agency/administration-government] However "coalition" or "government" are also used when one does not refer to a specific coalition (note that the two terms have slightly different meanings).
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Usually, sovereign states have several levels of administrative division.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Common names for the principal (largest) administrative divisions include: states (subnational states, rather than sovereign states), provinces, lands, oblasts and regions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] These in turn are often subdivided into smaller administrative units known by names such as comarcas, raions or districts, which are further subdivided into municipalities, communes or communities constituting the smallest units of subdivision (the local governments).
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Some administrative division names (such as departments, cantons, prefectures, counties or governorates) can be used for principal, second-level, or third-level divisions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] The levels of administrative divisions and their structure largely varies by country (and sometimes within a single country).
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Usually the smaller the country is (by area or population), the fewer levels of administrative divisions it has.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] For example, Vatican City does not have any administrative subdivisions, and Monaco has only one level (both are city-states), while such countries as France and Pakistan have five levels each.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] The United States is composed of states, possessions, territories, and a federal district, each with varying numbers of subdivisions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] The principal administrative division of a country is sometimes called the "*first-level* (or *first-order*) administrative division" or "first administrative level".
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Its next subdivision might be called "second-level administrative division" or "second administrative level" and so on.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] An alternative terminology is provided by the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics which terms the principal division as the second level or NUTS-2.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Communities united in a federation under a federal government are more specifically known as federated states.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] A federated state may be referred to as a province, region, canton, land, governorate, oblast, emirate, or country.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Administrative units that are not federated or confederated but enjoy a greater degree of autonomy or self-government than other territories within the same country can be considered autonomous regions or de facto constituent states of that country.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] This relationship is by some authors called a federacy or asymmetric federalism.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] An example is the autonomous republic of Karakalpakstan within Uzbekistan.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Due to variations in their use worldwide, consistency in the translation of terms from non-English to English is sometimes difficult to maintain.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] In many of the following terms originating from British cultural influence, areas of relatively low mean population density might bear a title of an entity one would expect to be either larger or smaller.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] There is no fixed rule, for "all politics is local" as is perhaps well demonstrated by their relative lack of systemic order.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] In the realm of self-government, any of these can and does occur along a stretch of road—which for the most part is passing through rural, unsettled countryside.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Since the terms are administrative political divisions of the local regional government, their exact relationship and definitions are subject to home rule considerations, tradition, as well as state statute law and local governmental (administrative) definition and control.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] In British cultural legacy, some territorial entities began with fairly expansive counties which encompass an appreciably large area, but were divided over time into a number of smaller entities.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Within those entities are the large and small cities or towns, which may or may not be the county seat.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Some of the world's larger cities culturally, if not officially, span several counties, and those crossing state or provincial boundaries have much in common culturally as well, but are rarely incorporated within the same municipal government.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] Many sister cities share a water boundary, which quite often serves as a border of both cities and counties.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] For example, Cambridge and Boston, Massachusetts appear to the casual traveler as one large city, while locally they each are quite culturally different and occupy different counties.
[src:government-agency/administrative-division] General terms for these incorporated places include "municipality", "settlement", "locality", and "populated place".
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law deals with the decision-making of administrative units of government that are part of the executive branch in such areas as international trade, manufacturing, the environment, taxation, broadcasting, immigration, and transport.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law expanded greatly during the 20th century, as legislative bodies worldwide created more government agencies to regulate the social, economic and political spheres of human interaction.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Civil law countries often have specialized administrative courts that review these decisions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Brazil, administrative cases are typically heard either by the Federal Courts (in matters concerning the Federal Union) or by the Public Treasury divisions of State Courts (in matters concerning the States).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In 1998 a constitutional reform led by the government of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso introduced regulatory agencies as a part of the executive branch.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Since 1988, Brazilian administrative law has been strongly influenced by the judicial interpretations of the constitutional principles of public administration (Art.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] 37 of the Federal Constitution): legality, impersonality, publicity of administrative acts, morality and efficiency.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Chile, the President of the Republic exercises the administrative function, in collaboration with several ministries or other authorities with *ministerial rank*.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Each ministry has one or more under-secretaries that act through public service to meet public needs.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] There is no single specialized court to deal with actions against the administrative entities, but there are several specialized courts and procedures of review.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law in China was virtually non-existent before the economic reform era initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Since the 1980s China has constructed a new legal framework for administrative law, establishing control mechanisms for overseeing the bureaucracy, and disciplinary committees for the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In 1989, China established its Administrative Litigation Law, which provides an avenue for people to challenge government action.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In 2014, it was amended to lower the burdens on those challenging administrative actions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In 1990, the Administrative Supervision Regulations (行政检查条例) and the Administrative Reconsideration Regulations (行政复议条例) were passed.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The 1993 State Civil Servant Provisional Regulations (国家公务员暂行条例) changed the way government officials were selected and promoted, requiring that they pass exams and yearly appraisals, and introducing a rotation system.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The three regulations have been amended and upgraded into laws.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In 1994, the State Compensation Law (国家赔偿法) was passed, followed by the Administrative Penalties Law (行政处罚法) in 1996.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative Compulsory Law was enforced in 2012.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The General Administrative Procedure Law is underway.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In France, there is a dual jurisdictional system with the judiciary branch responsible for civil law and criminal law, and the administrative branch having jurisdiction when a government institution is involved.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Most claims against the national or local governments as well as claims against private bodies providing public services are handled by administrative courts, which use the *Conseil d'État* (Council of State) as a court of last resort for both ordinary and special courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The main administrative courts are the *tribunaux administratifs* and appeal courts are the *cours administratives d'appel*.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Special administrative courts include the National Court of Asylum Right as well as military, medical and judicial disciplinary bodies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The French body of administrative law is called "*droit administratif*".
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] French administrative law, the basis of continental administrative law, has had a strong influence on administrative laws in several other countries such as Belgium, Greece, Turkey and Tunisia.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Germany, administrative law (German: *Verwaltungsrecht*) includes all law that specifically governs the legal relationships between public authorities and private persons, and that is not more precisely described as constitutional law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] It sets out the tasks, aims and powers, as well as the organization and procedure, for all public authorities (German: *Behörden*).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] As a field of legal study, administrative law has been differentiated from other branches of public law since the late 19th century in Germany; the precise delimitations of "administration" as a concept, however, are in contention.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law defines all aspects of public administration in the modern German state, whose legal culture emphasizes private persons' subjective rights (also, pursuant to art.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] 19IV of the current German Constitution of 1949, such rights must be fully justiciable).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The final say on the interpretation of the law lies with the courts of administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*), and the law usually permits close judicial scrutiny of public authorities' exercise of discretion.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] German legal scholarship does not have an agreed-upon definition for public administration.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In one sense, administration – more precisely, everything that is subject to administrative law – is conceptualized as being all state activity of a certain type (material definition of public administration).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] There is some danger of circular reasoning, since the formal categorization of the organizational unit may, in turn, derive from some material conception of its function.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] This discussion is of seen as being of particular importance when considering the role of administrative law in maintaining the division of government powers.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] For this purpose, a traditional approach tries negatively to define administration by subtracting those operations of the state which cannot be called administration, namely law-making and adjudication.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Using this negative definition, though, requires law-making and adjudication to be defined first, and leaves some activities that are a poor fit for the term "administration", such as the cabinet government's political leadership decisions, within the bounds of the definition.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Positive definitions abound, but none has won out over the others, or been entirely convincing to scholars of German administrative law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] 'special administrative law') – e.g. police law, urban planning law, or local government law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The is not a full codification of the generally applicable ground rules of German administrative law, since it mostly only determines the procedure to be followed by public authorities in the fulfillment of their tasks, rather than mandating the substance of public administration.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The VwVfG is a federal law that only applies to administration carried out by the German federal authorities.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] All 16 German *Länder* have, however, enacted a Law on Administrative Procedure of their own that is nearly word-for-word identical with the federal VwVfG.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The standard form of administrative is the *Verwaltungsakt* (administrative ordinance).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Pursuant to VwVfG § 35, an administrative ordinance exists where: a public authority (1) issues any decree, decision, or other official measure (2), in a matter of public law (3), with immediate legal effects outside the administration (4), to put in place a rule for an individual case (5).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The law governing the adjudication of questions of administrative law before the courts of general administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*) is the Code on Administrative Courts (German: *Verwaltungsgerichtsordnung*, abbreviated VwGO), which was enacted in 1960.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The VwGO also does not apply to the courts of special administrative jurisdiction over tax disputes (German: *Finanzgerichte*) or over social benefits disputes (German: *Sozialgerichte*).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Italy, administrative law is known as *Diritto amministrativo*, a branch of public law whose rules govern the organization of the public administration and the activities of the pursuit of the public interest of the public administration and the relationship between this and the citizens.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Its genesis is related to the principle of division of powers of the State.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The administrative power, originally called "executive", is to organize resources and people whose function is devolved to achieve the public interest objectives as defined by the law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In the Netherlands administrative law provisions are usually contained in the various laws about public services and regulations.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] There is however also a single General Administrative Law Act (*Algemene wet bestuursrecht* or Awb), which is a rather good sample of procedural laws in Europe.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] It applies both to the making of administrative decisions and the judicial review of these decisions in courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Another act about judicial procedures in general is the *Algemene termijnenwet* (General time provisions act), with general provisions about time schedules in procedures.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] On the basis of the Awb, citizens can oppose a decision (*besluit*) made by an administrative agency (*bestuursorgaan*) within the administration and apply for judicial review in courts if unsuccessful.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Before going to court, citizens must usually first object to the decision with the administrative body that made it.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] This procedure allows for the administrative body to correct possible mistakes themselves and is used to filter cases before going to court.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Sometimes, instead of *bezwaar*, a different system is used called *administratief beroep* (administrative appeal).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The difference with *bezwaar* is that *administratief beroep* is filed with a different administrative body, usually a higher ranking one, than the administrative body that made the primary decision.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] *Administratief beroep* is available only if the law on which the primary decision is based specifically provides for it.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] An example involves objecting to a traffic ticket with the district attorney (*officier van justitie*), after which the decision can be appealed in court.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Unlike France or Germany, there are no special administrative courts of first instance in the Netherlands, but regular courts have an administrative "chamber" which specializes in administrative appeals.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Sweden, there is a system of administrative courts that considers only administrative law cases and is completely separate from the system of general courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] This system has three tiers, with 12 county administrative courts (*förvaltningsrätt*) as the first tier, four administrative courts of appeal (*kammarrätt*) as the second tier, and the Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden (*Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*) as the third tier.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Migration cases are handled in a two-tier system, effectively within the system of general administrative courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Three of the administrative courts serve as migration courts (*migrationsdomstol*) with the Administrative Court of Appeal in Stockholm serving as the Migration Court of Appeal (*Migrationsöverdomstolen*), from which appeals may go to the *Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Taiwan the recently enacted *Constitutional Procedure Act* (憲法訴訟法) in 2019 (former *Constitutional Interpretation Procedure Act, 1993*), the **Justices of the Constitutional Court** of Judicial Yuan of Taiwan is in charge of judicial interpretation.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] As of 2019, this council has made 757 interpretations.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In Turkey, the lawsuits against the acts and actions of the national or local governments and public bodies are handled by administrative courts which are the main administrative courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The decisions of the administrative courts are checked by the Regional Administrative Courts and Council of State.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Council of State as a court of last resort is exactly similar to Conseil d'État in France.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law in Ukraine is a homogeneous legal substance isolated in a system of jurisprudence characterized as: (1) a branch of law; (2) a science; (3) a discipline.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Generally speaking, most countries that follow the principles of common law have developed procedures for judicial review that limit the reviewability of decisions made by administrative law bodies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Often these procedures are coupled with legislation or other common law doctrines that establish standards for proper rulemaking.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law may also apply to the review of decisions of so-called semi-public bodies, such as non-profit corporations, disciplinary boards, and other decision-making bodies that affect the legal rights of members of a particular group or entity.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] While administrative decision-making bodies are often controlled by larger governmental units, their decisions could be reviewed by a court of general jurisdiction under some principle of judicial review based upon due process (United States) or fundamental justice (Canada).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Judicial review of administrative decisions is different from an administrative appeal.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] When sitting in review of a decision, the Court will only look at the method in which the decision was arrived at, whereas in an administrative appeal, the correctness of the decision itself will be examined, usually by a higher body in the agency.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] This difference is vital in appreciating administrative law in common law countries.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The scope of judicial review may be limited to certain questions of fairness, or whether the administrative action is *ultra vires*.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative Procedure Act and New York State law).
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Administrative law, as laid down by the Supreme Court of India, has also recognized two more grounds of judicial review which were recognized but not applied by English Courts, namely legitimate expectation and proportionality.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The powers to review administrative decisions are usually established by statute but were originally developed from the royal prerogative writs of English law, such as the writ of mandamus and the writ of certiorari.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In certain common law jurisdictions, such as India or Pakistan, the power to pass such writs is a Constitutionally guaranteed power.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] This power is seen as fundamental to the power of judicial review and an aspect of the independent judiciary.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In the United States, many government agencies are organized under the executive branch of government, although a few are part of the judicial or legislative branches.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In the federal government, the executive branch, led by the president, controls the federal executive departments, which are led by secretaries who are members of the United States Cabinet.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The many independent agencies of the United States government created by statutes enacted by Congress exist outside of the federal executive departments but are still part of the executive branch.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Congress has also created some special judicial bodies known as Article I tribunals to handle some areas of administrative law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The actions of executive agencies and independent agencies are the main focus of American administrative law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] In response to the rapid creation of new independent agencies in the early twentieth century (see discussion below), Congress enacted the Administrative Procedure Act (**APA**) in 1946.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Because the United States Constitution sets no limits on this tripartite authority of administrative agencies, Congress enacted the APA to establish fair administrative law procedures to comply with the constitutional requirements of due process.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Agency procedures are drawn from four sources of authority: the APA, organic statutes, agency rules, and informal agency practice.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Agencies can only act within their congressionally delegated authority, and must comply with the requirements of the APA.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] At the state level, the first version of the Model State Administrative Procedure Act was promulgated and published in 1946 by the Uniform Law Commission (ULC), in which year the Federal Administrative Procedure Act was drafted.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] It incorporates basic principles with only enough elaboration of detail to support essential features, therefore it is a "model", and not a "uniform", act.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] A model act is needed because state administrative law in the states is not uniform, and there are a variety of approaches used in the various states.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The present version is the 2010 Model State Administrative Procedure Act (**MSAPA**) which maintains the continuity with earlier ones.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The reason for the revision is that, in the past two decades state legislatures, dissatisfied with agency rule-making and adjudication, have enacted statutes that modify administrative adjudication and rule-making procedure.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The American Bar Association's official journal concerning administrative law is the *Administrative Law Review*, a quarterly publication that is managed and edited by students at the Washington College of Law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The agricultural sector is one of the most heavily regulated sectors in the U.S. economy, as it is regulated in various ways at the international, federal, state, and local levels.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] Consequently, administrative law is a significant component of the discipline of agricultural law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-law] The United States Department of Agriculture and its myriad agencies such as the Agricultural Marketing Service are the primary sources of regulatory activity, although other administrative bodies such as the Environmental Protection Agency play a significant regulatory role as well.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The **Administrative Procedure Act** (**APA**), (Pub.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] 237, enacted Jun 11, 1946, is the United States federal statute that governs the way in which administrative agencies of the federal government of the United States may propose and establish regulations, and it grants U.S. federal courts oversight over all agency actions.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] According to Hickman & Pierce, it is one of the most important pieces of United States administrative law, and serves as a sort of "constitution" for U.S. administrative law.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The APA applies to both the federal executive departments and the independent agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] U.S. senator Pat McCarran called the APA "a bill of rights for the hundreds of thousands of Americans whose affairs are controlled or regulated" by federal government agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The text of the APA can be found under Title 5 of the United States Code, beginning at Section 500.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Section 702 of the APA waives sovereign immunity, allowing people to sue a federal agency in court for non-monetary relief, such as an injunction or a declaratory judgment.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] There is a similar Model State Administrative Procedure Act (Model State APA), which was drafted by the National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws for oversight of state agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Not all states have adopted the model law wholesale, as of 2017.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The federal APA does not require systematic oversight of regulations prior to adoption, unlike the Model APA.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Each US state has passed its own version of the Administrative Procedure Act.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Beginning in 1933, President Franklin D.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Roosevelt and the Democratic Congress enacted several statutes that created new federal agencies as part of the New Deal legislative plan, established to guide the United States through the social and economic hardship caused by the Great Depression.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] However, the Congress became concerned about the expanding powers that these autonomous federal agencies now possessed, resulting in the enactment of the APA to regulate, standardize and oversee these federal agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The APA was born in a contentious political environment.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Professor George Shepard claims that Roosevelt's opponents and supporters fought over passage of the APA "in a pitched political battle for the life of the New Deal" itself.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] A 1946 House of Representatives report discusses the 10-year period of "painstaking and detailed study and drafting" that went into the APA.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Because of rapid growth in the administrative regulation of private conduct, Roosevelt ordered several studies of administrative methods and conduct during the early part of his four-term presidency.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Based on one study, Roosevelt commented that the practice of creating administrative agencies with the authority to perform both legislative and judicial work "threatens to develop a fourth branch of government for which there is no sanction in the Constitution".
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] In 1939, Roosevelt requested for Attorney General Frank Murphy to form a committee to investigate practices and procedures in American administrative law and suggest improvements.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] That committee's report, the *Final Report of Attorney General's Committee on Administrative Procedure*, contained detailed information about the development and procedures of the federal agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The *Final Report* defined a federal agency as a governmental unit with "the power to determine ... private rights and obligations" by rulemaking or adjudication.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The report applied that definition to the largest units of the federal government, and identified "nine executive departments and eighteen independent agencies".
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Overall, 51 federal agencies were identified in the report after including various subdivisions within the larger units.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] In reviewing the history of federal agencies, the *Final Report* noted that almost all agencies had undergone changes in name and political function.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Of the 51 federal agencies discussed in the *Final Report*, 11 were created by statute before the American Civil War.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] From 1865 to 1900, six new agencies were created, notably the Interstate Commerce Commission in 1887 in response to widespread criticism of the railroad industry.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] From 1900 to 1930, seventeen agencies were created by statute, and eighteen more had been created since.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The *Final Report* made several recommendations about standardizing administrative procedures, but Congress delayed action as the US entered World War II.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Five years after the report was made, Congress reintroduced the bill and President Harry S.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Truman signed the APA into law on June 11, 1946.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] In 1966, the Freedom of Information Act amended the APA to establish a system that requires federal agencies to disclose government information to the public.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] In response to the Watergate and COINTELPRO scandals, two further amendments were passed.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The Privacy Act of 1974 amended the APA to cover the government's handling of personal information, and in 1976, the Government in the Sunshine Act further clarified what portion of government meetings and documents were required to be public.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The Paperwork Reduction Act (1980), the Regulatory Flexibility Act (1980), and the Electronic Freedom of Information Act (1996) were further adjustments.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Although each US government agency is constituted within one branch of the government (judicial, legislative, or executive), an agency's authority often extends into the functions of other branches.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Without careful regulation, that can lead to unchecked authority in a particular area of government, violating the separation of powers, a concern that Roosevelt himself acknowledged.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] To provide constitutional safeguards, the APA creates a framework for regulating agencies and their roles.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] 4. to define the scope of judicial review.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The APA's provisions apply to many federal governmental institutions and agencies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Courts have also held that the U.S. president is not an agency under the APA.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The APA's capacity to hold accountable regulatory business monitors that oversee civil matters that apply "'soft' administrative law" is also limited.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The Supreme Court held that APA lawsuits seeking to enforce a contractual obligation to pay money must be brought in the Court of Federal Claims, not federal district courts.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The *Final Report* organized federal administrative action into two parts: adjudication and rulemaking.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Agency adjudication was broken down further into two distinct phases of formal and informal adjudication.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Formal adjudication involve a trial-like hearing with witness testimony, a written record, and a final decision.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Under informal adjudication, agency decisions are made without these formal procedures, instead using "inspections, conferences and negotiations".
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Because formal adjudication produces a record of proceedings and a final decision, it may be subject to judicial review.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] As for rulemaking resulting in agency rules and regulations, the *Final Report* noted that many agencies provided due process through hearings and investigations, but there was still a need for well-defined uniform standards for agency adjudication and rulemaking procedures.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] The APA requires that to set aside agency actions that are not subject to formal trial-like procedures (i.e. rulemaking), the court must conclude that the regulation is "arbitrary and capricious, an abuse of discretion, or otherwise not in accordance with the law".
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] However, Congress may further limit the scope of judicial review of agency actions by including such language in the authorizing statute.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] To set aside formal rulemaking or formal adjudication for which procedures are trial-like, a different standard of review allows courts to question agency actions more strongly.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] For such more formal actions, agency decisions must be supported by "substantial evidence" after the court reads the "whole record", which can be thousands of pages long.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Unlike arbitrary and capricious review, substantial evidence review gives the courts leeway to consider whether an agency's factual and policy determinations were warranted in light of all the information before the agency at the time of decision.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Accordingly, arbitrary and capricious review is understood to be more deferential to agencies than substantial evidence review is.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Arbitrary and capricious review allows agency decisions to stand as long as an agency can give a reasonable explanation for its decision based on the information that it had at the time.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] By virtue of their constitutional role, U.S. presidents can try to influence specific regulatory proposals before their finalization.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Within the Executive Office of the President is the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA), a federal subagency led by a presidential appointee that is widely viewed as working on the president's behalf during the regulatory review process.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Rules and regulations issued or proposed (see Notice of Proposed Rulemaking) by federal administrative agencies are published chronologically in the *Federal Register*.
[src:government-agency/administrative-procedure-act] Promulgated rules and regulations are then organized by topic in a separate publication called the Code of Federal Regulations.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] The **regions of Greece** (Greek: περιφέρειες, romanized: *periféreies*) are the country's thirteen second-level administrative entities, counting decentralized administrations of Greece as first-level.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] Regions are divided into regional units, known as prefectures until 2011.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] The current regions were established in July 1986 (the presidential decree officially establishing them was signed in 1987), by decision of the interior minister, Menios Koutsogiorgas, as second-level administrative entities, complementing the prefectures (Law 1622/1986).
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] Before 1986, there was a traditional division into broad historical–geographical regions (γεωγραφικά διαμερίσματα), which, however, was often arbitrary; not all of the pre-1986 traditional historical-geographic regions had official administrative bodies.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] As part of a decentralization process inspired by Interior Minister Alekos Papadopoulos, they were accorded more powers in the 1997 Kapodistrias reform of local and regional government.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] They were transformed into fully separate entities by the 2010 Kallikratis Plan (Law 3852/2010), which entered into effect on 1 January 2011.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] In the 2011 changes, the government-appointed general secretary (γενικός γραμματέας) was replaced with a popularly elected regional governor (περιφερειάρχης) and a regional council (περιφερειακό συμβούλιο) with five-year terms.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] Many powers of the prefectures, which were also abolished or reformed into regional units, were transferred to the region level.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] The regional organs of the central government were in turn replaced by seven decentralized administrations, which group from one to three regions under a government-appointed general secretary.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] Bordering the region of Central Macedonia there is one autonomous region, Mount Athos (*Agion Oros*, or "Holy Mountain"), an autonomous monastic community under Greek sovereignty.
[src:government-agency/administrative-regions-of-greece] It is located on the easternmost of the three large peninsulas protruding into the Aegean from the Chalkidiki peninsula.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] The **alphabet agencies**, or **New Deal agencies**, were the U.S. federal government agencies created as part of the New Deal of President Franklin D.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] The earliest agencies were created to combat the Great Depression in the United States and were established during Roosevelt's first 100 days in office in 1933.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] In total, at least 69 offices were created during Roosevelt's terms of office as part of the New Deal.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Some alphabet agencies were established by Congress, such as the Tennessee Valley Authority.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Others were established through Roosevelt executive orders, such as the Works Progress Administration and the Office of Censorship, or were part of larger programs such as the many that belonged to the Works Progress Administration.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Some of the agencies still exist today, while others have merged with other departments and agencies or were abolished.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] The agencies were sometimes referred to as alphabet soup.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] These powers were used to create many of the alphabet agencies.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Other laws were passed allowing the new bureaus to pass their own directives within a wide sphere of authority.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Even though the National Industrial Recovery Act was found to be unconstitutional, many of the agencies created under it remained.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Since the 1990s, the term "alphabet agencies" has been commonly used to describe the agencies of the U.S. national security state.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Many are members of the United States Intelligence Community, and several were founded or expanded in the aftermath of the September 11 attacks.
[src:government-agency/alphabet-agencies] Alphabet agencies in this sense of the term may also be called **three-letter agencies**, because they often use three-letter acronyms.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] A **government agency** or **state agency**, also known as an **appointed commission**, is a permanent or semi-permanent organization in the machinery of government (bureaucracy) that is responsible for the oversight and administration of specific functions, such as an administration.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] There is a notable variety of agency types.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Although usage differs, a government agency is normally distinct both from a department or ministry, and other types of public body established by government.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The functions of an agency are normally executive in character since different types of organizations (*such as commissions*) are most often constituted in an advisory role — this distinction is often blurred in practice however, it is not allowed.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] A government agency may be established by either a national government or a state government within a federal system.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Agencies can be established by legislation or by executive powers.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The autonomy, independence, and accountability of government agencies also vary widely.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Early examples of organizations that would now be termed a government agency include the British Navy Board, responsible for ships and supplies, which was established in 1546 by King Henry VIII and the British Commissioners of Bankruptcy established in 1570.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] From 1933, the New Deal saw growth in U.S. federal agencies, the "alphabet agencies" as they were used to deliver new programs created by legislation, such as the Federal Emergency Relief Administration.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] From the 1980s, as part of New Public Management, several countries including Australia and the United Kingdom developed the use of agencies to improve efficiency in public services.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Administrative law in France refers to *autorité administrative indépendante* (AAI) or Independent Administrative Authorities.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Independent Administrative Authorities in France may not be instructed or ordered to take specific actions by the government.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The General Secretariat for Macedonia and Thrace (Greek: Γενική Γραμματεία Μακεδονίας-Θράκης), previously Ministry for Macedonia and Thrace (Greek: Υπουργείο Μακεδονίας-Θράκης) is a government agency of the Hellenic Republic that is responsible for the Greek regions of Macedonia and Thrace.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The term *agency* in India has several meanings; for example, the Cabinet and the parliament Secretariat describes itself as a "*nodal agency* for coordination amongst the ministries of the Govt. of India".
[src:government-agency/government-agency] In the Netherlands, an agency (*agentschap*) is a part of a government ministry with its own management, budget, and financial administration, separate from the ministry to which it belongs.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The minister retains full control of an agency and has full ministerial responsibility for its activities.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Russia has had many government agencies throughout its history.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Today, Russian government agencies such as the FSB, FSO, and the GRU use Spetsnaz or other masked operators for any missions.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Other organizations include Kremlin and presidential security.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The Government agencies in Sweden are State controlled organizations who act independently to carry out the policies of the Government of Sweden.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The Ministries are relatively small and merely policy-making organizations, allowed to control agencies by policy decisions but not by direct orders.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] This means that while the agencies are subject to decisions made by the Government, Ministers are explicitly prohibited (so-called ban on *ministerstyre*) from interfering with the day-to-day operation in an agency or the outcome in individual cases as well.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] In addition to the State and its agencies, there are also local government agencies, which are extensions of municipalities and county councils.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Agencies in the United Kingdom are either executive agencies answerable to government ministers or non-departmental public bodies answerable directly to parliament or the devolved assemblies of the United Kingdom.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] They are also commonly known as Quangos.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Agencies can be created by enabling legislation by the Parliament of the United Kingdom, Scottish Parliament or the Welsh Parliament.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The Congress and President of the United States delegate specific authority to government agencies to regulate the complex facets of the modern American federal state.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Also, most of the 50 U.S. states have created similar government agencies.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Each state government is similar to the national government, with all but one having a bicameral legislature.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The term "government agency" or "administrative agency" usually applies to one of the independent agencies of the United States federal government, which exercise some degree of independence from the President's control.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Although the heads of independent agencies are often appointed by the government, they can usually be removed only for cause.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The heads of independent agencies work together in groups, such as a commission, board or council.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Independent agencies often function as miniature versions of the tripartite federal government with the authority to legislate (through the issuing or promulgation of regulations), to adjudicate disputes, and to enforce agency regulations.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Examples of independent agencies include the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), Federal Reserve Board, U.S.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:government-agency/government-agency] A broader definition of the term "government agency" also means the United States federal executive departments that include the President's cabinet-level departments and their sub-units.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Examples of these include the Department of Energy (DOE) and the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), which is a bureau of the Department of the Treasury.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Most federal agencies are created by Congress through "organic statutes," which define the scope of their authority.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] Because the Constitution does not expressly mention federal agencies, some commentators have called agencies the "headless fourth branch" of the federal government.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] However, most independent agencies are technically part of the executive branch, while others work within the legislative branch.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] By enacting the Administrative Procedure Act (APA) in 1946, Congress established means to oversee agency action through uniform administrative law procedures for setting regulations and adjudicating claims.
[src:government-agency/government-agency] The APA also establishes judicial review of agency action.
